<div class="divContent"  id="wrap">
                            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 150%;" >
 <img  src= "../images/poscr1.png" style="width:80px;height:57px">
<b>Learning objectives</b></div><br>

After completing this simulation experiment one should be able to </br>
<ul>
<li>	Model a given real system to an equivalent simplified model of single degree freedom system with suitable assumptions / idealisations.</br></li>
<li>	Calculate the natural frequency of undamped oscillation, critical damping constant and critical damping ratio of the proposed single degree freedom system.</br></li>  
<li>	Study the response of the system for different harmonic excitation frequency and amplitude of the base.</br></li>
<li>	Calculate the transmissibility ratio and phase angle as a function of forcing frequency</br></li>
</ul>

<h3 style="color:#997e11">
Forced vibration of single degree of freedom system- Base excitation</h3></br>
Introduction </br></br>
In many cases, dynamical system is excited by motion of the support point or base as shown in the Fig 1.
 The base excitation system may be of vehicle suspension system or earthquake response of a structure or a performance
 of a precision machine located close proximity of a vibrating structure as shown in Fig 2. The motion of the base causes the main system to vibrate as a function of excitation frequency and amplitude. 
 Base excitation models the behaviour of a vibration isolation system and is applicable in the analysis of preventing the excitations from passing from a vibrating base through its mount into a structure. 
</p>

<p>
<figure>
<img src="../images/fvss1.png" style="width:404px;height:344px" >
<img src="../images/fvss2.png" style="width:460px;height:260px"></br>
  <figcaption>Fig 1: Dynamic vibration absorber in steel stack</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure>
<img src="../images/fvss3.png" style="width:357px;height:231px">
<img src="../images/fvss4.png" style="width:452px;height:151px"></br>
  <figcaption>Fig 2: Dynamic vibration absorber PCB</figcaption>
</figure>
To study the response of a dynamic system for base excitation, given real system  will be modelled as a equivalent single 
degree spring-mass system as shown in Fig 3 and it is excited by a harmonic input y(t)=Y sin?t applied at the base. The proposed single degree
spring-mass system can be thought of as representing a single mode of vibration in a real system, whose natural frequency and damping coefficient coincide with that of proposed spring-mass system.  </p>

<figure><img src="../images/fvss5.png" style="width:410px;height:248px"></br>
  <figcaption>
Fig 3: A single degree of freedom system and vibration absorber system</figcaption>
</figure>

Differential equation of motion of the system is given by,</br>

<img src="../images/equations/7VpuOTFH.png" style="width:262px;height:57px" >  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     ----(1)</br>
The general solution of this mathematical model consists of two parts, the complementary
function which is the solution of the homogenous equation, and the particular integral. The
particular solution to the preceding equation is a steady-state oscillation of same
frequency ω as that of excitation. We can assume particular solution to be of the form</br>


<img src="../images/equations/igXWniXu.png" style="width:211px;height:28px" > &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-----(2)</br>

Where X is the amplitude of oscillation and  is the phase lag of the displacement with
respect to the exciting force.
By substituting the equation 2 in equation 1, amplitude X and phase  is given as,</br>


<img src="../images/equations/yHmAwfAr.png
" style="width:270px;height:80px" > &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-----(3)</br>

and 
<img src="../images/equations/WRMc33pN.png
" style="width:223px;height:78px" > &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-----(4)</br>


Where,
ω is the excitation frequency
k is the equivalent spring stiffness<br>

m is the equivalent mass of the system
c is the equivalent damping coefficient<br>

The non-dimensional form of expression 3 and 4 are given by,<br>


<img src="../images/equations/p6XsFmrM.png
" style="width:585px;height:94px" > &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;----(5)<br>
<img src="../images/equations/mLImAVbt.png
" style="width:234px;height:134px" > &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;----(6)<br>


Where,
The above equations may be represented in terms of following quantities:<br>
<img src="../images/equations/e0m2G5Vv.png
" style="width:106px;height:60px" > = natural frequency of un-damped oscillation<br>
<img src="../images/equations/ks7iAzx6.png 
" style="width:118px;height:36px" > = critical damping constant<br>
<img src="../images/equations/mozDv188.png 
" style="width:57px;height:40px" >= damping ratio<br>
Xst= F0/k<br>
<img src="../images/equations/cKDK3nYN.png 
" style="width:16px;height:28px" > is the frequency ratio<br>



The quantity X/Xst is called the magnification factor, amplification factor, or amplitude ratio.<br>
The variations X/Xst and  of and with the frequency ratio η and the damping ratio ξ are<br>
shown in fig 3.<br>





<img src="../images/fvss6.png" style="width:737px;height:391px"></br>

<p>
Lets try to understand these equations by doing a few simple simulations, go to next tab procedure to find out how to run the simulation to EXPLORE (expR) and to EXPERIMENT (expT).</br>
 A talking tutorial or a self-running demo with narration can be seen at EXPLAIN (expN).</br>

